    bio: "Abu Abdullah Muhammad Ibn Battuta was born in Tangier, Morocco, in 1304 into a family of Islamic legal scholars. At the age of twenty-one, he set out on a pilgrimage to Mecca — a journey that would stretch into nearly three decades of almost continuous travel across the known world. By the time he returned home for the final time, he had covered an estimated 75,000 miles, a distance unmatched by any individual traveler until the age of steam.\n\nHis journeys carried him through North Africa, the Horn of Africa, the Middle East, Central Asia, South Asia, Southeast Asia, and China. He served as a judge in the Maldives, narrowly survived shipwrecks in the Indian Ocean, witnessed the Black Death sweeping through Syria and Egypt, and visited the court of the Golden Horde on the Russian steppe. Everywhere he went, he observed local customs, legal traditions, and political systems with the keen eye of a trained jurist, producing one of the most valuable firsthand accounts of the fourteenth-century Islamic world and beyond.\n\nUpon his return to Morocco, the Marinid sultan commissioned the scholar Ibn Juzayy to record Ibn Battuta's accounts in a work known as the Rihla, meaning \"The Journey.\" While some historians have questioned certain details and suspect embellishments, the text remains an irreplaceable source for understanding trade networks, religious practices, and daily life across medieval Africa and Asia. Ibn Battuta died in relative obscurity around 1368, but his Rihla has since earned him recognition as one of the greatest travelers in human history, a figure whose curiosity and endurance rival those of Marco Polo."
